postcontent: I am selling my Browning BAR semi-auto in 30.06 caliber. It's a Grade II model, which means it has the engravings on the blued receiver. It has a Bushnell Banner 3-9X50 scope, which was mounted by the last owner. There is no rear sight, but that can be easily replaced if necessary. There are a few dings in the stock, and a crack in the fore end that has been repaired and is solid. The bluing is in great shape with only a few blemishes and absolutely no rust. The condition is great for a 1967 rifle. It went bang every time I fired it, and it ejects strong without jamming. I don't hunt and this one is a safe queen.$950 obo. I will include a vintage leather sling, and whatever 30-06 ammo I have (maybe 20 something rounds). You must be willing to show good guy IDs and complete a bill of sale. title: For Sale:  1951 Colt Cobra
postcontent: 1951 Colt Cobra .38 Special, near mint condition. Please examine all pictures carefully and ask questions if you have any. More pictures available upon request. I bought this because I wanted a nearly perfect early Cobra to be part of my small Colt collection. I have never fired it during my ownership but I have tested the function with snap caps and it works perfect. I have no reason to think it would not function as intended, I simply did not want to take the chance of additional wear or damage. Every part of the action is incredibly smooth and tight with a crisp clean break. Timing is right on, lockup is tight as new, and no slop or play in anything. It's as if it just came out of the box...which I unfortunately do not have. The original plastic grips are perfect and there is only very minor high spot wear near the front of the cylinder crane. The finish is original. There is the typical Cobra paint flake between the frame face and rear of the cylinder as shown in the 3rd picture. I've seen many this way and I believe it has to do with the aluminum frame. Any speckling or irregular gloss/flat coloring on the finish is lint or oil that was not wiped off completely. The frame and crane serial numbers match. I've cleaned, examined, and re-lubed the internals as I have done with every firearm I've owned and this is just as mint on the inside as it is on the outside. I was interested in this because of the exceptional condition and the low serial number. The most famous Cobra in history is serial #2744LW. This one is #2338LW. It's interesting to me to know only about 400 units separate the two...a fun fact for my own amusement. $1000, no trades. MN permit to purchase/carry and valid driver's license required. A bill of sale will be signed. I will ship to an FFL, shipping rates would apply.
